1.The core components of Linux (kernel, user space, init/systemd)
===  Architecture of Linux  ===
   Linux is based on ASK architecture.
   A- Application/User.
      It is a graphical user interface (GUI) leval.
      The Linux application layer (or user space) is the topmost level of the Linux architecture. 
      In this layer user-interact with software, such as web browsers, desktop environments (GNOME, KDE), and terminal applications, operate.
      
   S- Shell
      Shell is a command line interface (CLI).
      it is the middle layer between application and kernal.
      it interprets linux commands into OS(kernal) understandable language. 
      Various linux distributions like Ubuntu, Fedora, cent os, etc come with a default shell (such as Bash) pre-installed to provide a command-line interface for the user.
      
   K- Kernal
      Linux kernal is the heart of linux.
      It was written in C language.
      Even though linux kernal is written in C language, we can not directly interact with kernal.
      Because kernal only accept structured system calls(0,1), not human-readeble commands.
      Shell interprete tht user commands into system calls in background.

   init/systemd -
      This are the very first process that runs (assigned PID 1) once the Linux kernel loads. Its job is to "initialize" the system by 
      starting background services (daemons) like networking, login screens, and database servers.
      
           Init (Traditional): Refers to the older standard, specifically SysVinit. It started services one after another (sequentially), 
           which often made booting slower.
           
           systemd (Modern): The modern replacement for SysVinit, now used by default in almost all major distributions like Ubuntu, Fedora, and Debian. 
           It starts many services at the same time (in parallel), leading to faster boot times.
           
2.How processes are created and managed?
=> A process is an instance of a program that is currently executing.
A program stored on disk becomes a process when it starts running.Each process is uniquely identified by a Process ID (PID).

How a process is created (fork & exec)

When a user runs a command, the shell asks the Linux kernel to create a new process using fork().
fork() creates a child process, which is a copy of the parent process.
After that, the child process uses exec() to load and run the required program.
The child keeps the same PID but its memory is replaced with the new program.
Once execution finishes, the process exits and releases system resources.

Parent and child processes

Linux processes follow a hierarchical structure.
The process that creates another process is the parent, and the newly created one is the child.
All processes are descendants of the first system process.
If a parent process ends before the child, the child is adopted by the system’s first process.

Process states

During its lifetime, a process may be in different states:
Running – executing on the CPU
Sleeping – waiting for input or I/O
Stopped – paused manually or by the system
Terminated – finished execution
These states help the kernel manage CPU and resources efficiently.

Process scheduling and CPU usage

The Linux kernel uses a scheduler to decide which process runs on the CPU.
Each process is given a small time slice for execution.
Fast switching between processes allows multiple processes to appear as if they are running at the same time.

Process control and signals

Linux manages processes using signals.
Signals allow processes to be stopped, resumed, or terminated when required.
They help control unresponsive or misbehaving processes.

Role of systemd in process management

systemd is the first user-space process started by the kernel and has PID 1.
It starts system services, manages background processes, and monitors their health.
If a service fails, systemd can automatically restart it.

3.Understand how Linux works under the hood and What systemd does and why it matters ?
=> Linux runs as a layered system where control gradually moves from hardware to user applications. When the system is powered on, 
the firmware initializes the hardware and loads the bootloader, which is responsible for locating and loading the Linux kernel into memory. 
Once loaded, the kernel takes full control of the system. The kernel is the core of Linux and is responsible for managing hardware resources, 
memory, CPU scheduling, device drivers, and handling system calls from user programs. At this stage, only the kernel is running, and no user 
services or applications are available.

After the kernel initializes essential subsystems, it starts the first user-space process, which always has process ID 1. In modern Linux systems, 
this process is systemd. systemd plays a critical role in bringing the system to a usable state. It is responsible for starting system services, 
managing their dependencies, and ensuring they run in the correct order. systemd starts services in parallel wherever possible, which significantly 
improves system boot time compared to older initialization systems. It also continuously monitors services during runtime and can automatically 
restart them if they fail.

In addition to service management, systemd controls the overall system state and handles system startup, shutdown, and reboot sequences. 
It provides centralized logging for system and service events, which helps in tracking system behavior and diagnosing issues. 
By managing long-running processes, handling dependencies, and maintaining system stability, systemd acts as the central manager of the 
user-space environment. Together, the kernel and systemd form the foundation of a running Linux system, enabling user applications and services 
to operate reliably on top of the hardware.
      

   
